@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction

@cindex introduction
@cindex EIGHTBOL compiler
@cindex 8-bit programming
@cindex retro computing

Welcome to EIGHTBOL, your friendly guide to programming classic video game
consoles and computers! If you've ever wanted to create your own games for
systems like the Atari 7800, Nintendo Entertainment System, or even the
Intellivision, you're in the right place.

@section What is Programming?

Before we dive into EIGHTBOL, let's take a moment to understand
what programming really is. Imagine you're giving instructions to a very
patient but not very bright friend. You need to break down every single
step of what you want them to do.

For example, if you want your friend to make a peanut butter sandwich:

@enumerate
@item Go to the kitchen
@item Open the bread bag
@item Take out 2 slices of bread
@item Put them on a plate
@item Open the peanut butter jar
@item Get a knife
@item Scoop peanut butter onto one slice
@item Spread it evenly
@item Put the knife down
@item Put the other slice on top
@item Give me the sandwich
@end enumerate

Programming is  exactly like  this! You write  step-by-step instructions
that  tell  a computer  exactly  what  to  do.  The difference  is  that
computers are incredibly fast and never get bored or distracted.

@section Meet EIGHTBOL

EIGHTBOL is based on COBOL (COmmon  Business Oriented Language)  was created in 1959  to help
businesses process  data and  generate reports. Unlike  many programming
languages  that use  cryptic symbols,  EIGHTBOL was  designed to  read like
English sentences.

Here's what a simple EIGHTBOL instruction looks like:

@example
ADD 1 TO Counter.
@end example

See how it reads almost like a sentence? That's the beauty of EIGHTBOL!

@section What is EIGHTBOL?

EIGHTBOL is  an EIGHTBOL variant designed for creating  games on
classic 8-bit  and 16-bit computers.  It takes EIGHTBOL programs  you write
and  converts  them  into  the low-level  instructions  that  these  old
computers understand.

Think  of EIGHTBOL  as  a translator  between  human-friendly EIGHTBOL  and
machine-friendly assembly language.

@section Why Learn EIGHTBOL?

Creating games  for classic systems teaches  you fundamental programming
concepts that apply to all programming:

@itemize
@item @strong{Problem Solving}: Breaking complex problems into small steps
@item @strong{Logic}: Making decisions and controlling program flow
@item @strong{Data Management}: Organizing and manipulating information
@item @strong{Performance}: Writing efficient code for limited hardware
@end itemize

Plus, you'll have the satisfaction of creating games that run on real
vintage hardware!

@section Your First Mental Model

Imagine your program as a recipe book. Each recipe (procedure) contains
step-by-step instructions. Your data is like the ingredients stored in
the pantry (memory).

When you run a program, it's like following a recipe: you get ingredients
from storage, follow the steps, and create something new.

@section What You'll Learn

By the end of this manual, you'll be able to:

@itemize
@item Write complete EIGHTBOL programs
@item Create variables to store data
@item Use arithmetic and logic operations
@item Control program flow with conditions and loops
@item Organize code into reusable procedures
@item Debug and fix common programming errors
@item Compile programs for multiple classic game systems
@end itemize

@section Target Platforms

EIGHTBOL generates assembly code for these CPU architectures:

@table @asis
@item 6502
MOS Technology 6502 8-bit processor
@item Z80
Zilog Z80 8-bit processor
@item CP1610
General Instrument CP1610 16-bit processor
@item M68K
Motorola 68000 series 16-bit/32-bit processors
@end table

@section Ready to Start?

Programming can seem intimidating at first, but remember: every expert
programmer was once a beginner. We'll take it one small step at a time,
and you'll be surprised how quickly concepts start to click.

Let's begin your programming journey!

