@node Quick Start
@chapter Quick Start

@cindex quick start
@cindex hello world
@cindex first program

Congratulations! You're about to write your first computer program. We'll
start with something simple but complete. By the end of this chapter,
you'll have a working program that you can compile and run.

@section Understanding Program Structure

Before we write code, let's understand how EIGHTBOL programs are organized.
Think of an EIGHTBOL program like a recipe book with specific sections:

@table @asis
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION
The title page - tells us what this program is
@item ENVIRONMENT DIVISION
The kitchen setup - tells us what tools we need
@item DATA DIVISION
The ingredient list - defines our data storage
@item PROCEDURE DIVISION
The cooking instructions - the actual program logic
@end table

@section Your First Object: Score Counter

Let's create a simple object that manages a score counter. This will teach us
about classes, methods, and data management in EIGHTBOL.

Create a file called @file{ScoreCounter.cob} with this content:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. ScoreCounter.

OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.
        COPY WorkingStorage.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "Initialize".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            MOVE 0 TO Current-Score.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Initialize".

        METHOD-ID. "Increment".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            IF Current-Score < Max-Score THEN
                ADD 1 TO Current-Score
            END-IF.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Increment".

        METHOD-ID. "GetScore".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            GOBACK GIVING Current-Score.
        END METHOD "GetScore".

        METHOD-ID. "IsComplete".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            IF Current-Score >= Max-Score THEN
                GOBACK GIVING 1
            ELSE
                GOBACK GIVING 0
            END-IF.
        END METHOD "IsComplete".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS ScoreCounter.
@end example

Let's break this down line by line:

@table @code
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
This marks the beginning of our object's identity section
@item CLASS-ID. ScoreCounter.
We name our class "ScoreCounter"
@item OBJECT.
This defines the object structure
@item DATA DIVISION.
Here we define our object's data storage
@item COPY WorkingStorage.
Includes system-provided data definitions
@item METHOD-ID. "Initialize".
A method to set up the object
@item MOVE 0 TO Current-Score.
Reset the score to 0
@item METHOD-ID. "Increment".
A method to increase the score
@item IF Current-Score < Max-Score THEN
Only increment if we haven't reached the maximum
@item METHOD-ID. "GetScore".
A method to retrieve the current score
@item GOBACK GIVING Current-Score.
Return the current score value
@end table

@section Compiling Your Program

Now let's turn this EIGHTBOL program into assembly code that a computer can
understand.

In your Lisp environment, load EIGHTBOL and compile:

@example
;; Load EIGHTBOL
(asdf:load-system :eightbol)

;; Compile for the 6502 processor (Atari 7800/NES)
;; Include copybook directories for COPY statements
(eightbol:compile-file "counter.cob" :cpu 6502
                       :include '("Source/Generated" "Source/Classes"))
@end example

This creates a file called @file{counter.s} containing 6502 assembly code.

@section Running Your Program

The assembly code needs to be assembled into machine code and run on
the target platform. This usually involves:

@enumerate
@item Using an assembler (like 64tass for 6502)
@item Linking with system libraries
@item Running on an emulator or real hardware
@end enumerate

For learning purposes, you can examine the generated assembly code to
see how your EIGHTBOL translates to machine instructions.

@section Try This!

Modify the counter program to count down from 10 to 1 instead of up.
Hint: Use SUBTRACT instead of ADD, and change the UNTIL condition.

@section What You Learned

In this chapter, you learned:

@itemize
@item How EIGHTBOL programs are structured into divisions
@item How to declare variables with PIC clauses
@item How to use PERFORM for looping
@item How to display output
@item How to compile EIGHTBOL to assembly
@end itemize

Great job on your first program! In the next chapter, we'll dive deeper
into variables and data types.

@node Language Reference
@chapter Language Reference

@cindex language reference
@cindex syntax
@cindex EIGHTBOL features

Now that you understand the basics, let's explore EIGHTBOL's features in detail.
We'll build your understanding step by step, with examples you can try.

@section The Recipe Book: Program Structure

Imagine an EIGHTBOL program as a cookbook. Just like a cookbook has sections
for ingredients and instructions, an EIGHTBOL program has divisions that
organize different types of information.

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.      @c What is this object?
CLASS-ID. Player.

OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.            @c What data do we need?
        COPY PlayerData.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.       @c What methods do we have?

        METHOD-ID. "AddPoints".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION USING Points-To-Add.
            ADD Points-To-Add TO Player-Score.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "AddPoints".

        METHOD-ID. "GetScore".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            GOBACK GIVING Player-Score.
        END METHOD "GetScore".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS Player.
@end example

Each division has a specific purpose:

@table @asis
@item IDENTIFICATION DIVISION
Like the title page - tells us what this class is
@item CLASS-ID
Names our class (like a blueprint for objects)
@item OBJECT
Defines the object structure and behavior
@item DATA DIVISION
Like the ingredient list - defines our object's data storage
@item PROCEDURE DIVISION
Like the methods - defines our object's behavior
@end itemize

@section Naming Your Class

Every EIGHTBOL class needs an identity. This is like giving your blueprint
a name and author.

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Space-Invaders-Clone.
AUTHOR. Your Name Here.
DATE-WRITTEN. 2026.
@end example

The @code{CLASS-ID} is required and must be unique. Think of it as
your class's name.

EIGHTBOL supports object-oriented programming with:

@table @code
@item CLASS-ID. name.
Defines a class (like a blueprint for objects)
@item METHOD-ID. name.
Defines a method within a class
@item OBJECT.
Contains the data and methods for the class
@end table

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Player-Character.
AUTHOR. Game Developer.
DATE-WRITTEN. 2024.
@end example

@section Storing Information: Variables

Variables are like containers that hold data. In EIGHTBOL, we declare
variables in the DATA DIVISION, just like listing ingredients before
cooking.

@subsection Understanding PIC Clauses

PIC (Picture) clauses describe what kind of data a variable can hold.
Think of them as labels on storage containers.

@example
DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 Player-Name PIC X(20).        @c Up to 20 letters
01 Player-Score PIC 9(5).        @c 5-digit number (0-99999)
01 Game-Over-Flag PIC X.         @c Single character: 'Y' or 'N'
01 Bonus-Multiplier PIC 9V9.     @c Decimal number: 1.5, 2.0, etc.
@end example

@table @code
@item PIC X
Single character (letter or symbol)
@item PIC X(n)
String of n characters
@item PIC 9
Single digit (0-9)
@item PIC 9(n)
n-digit number
@item PIC 9V9
Decimal number (like 1.5)
@end table

@strong{Important:} EIGHTBOL doesn't support string variables (PIC X).
Use byte arrays or numeric variables instead.

@subsection Try This: Variable Declaration

Create variables for a simple game character:

@example
DATA DIVISION.
COPY CharacterData.
@end example

What happens if you try to store "SuperLongCharacterName" in Character-Name?

@subsection Arrays: Storing Lists

Sometimes you need to store collections of data, like high scores or
inventory items.

@example
DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01 High-Scores PIC 9(5) OCCURS 10 TIMES.
01 Inventory PIC X(20) OCCURS 50 TIMES.

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Store-High-Score.
    MOVE Player-Score TO High-Scores(1).
    GOBACK.
@end example

Access array elements with parentheses: @code{Array-Name(index)}

@strong{Note:} EIGHTBOL arrays are 1-based (start at 1, not 0 like some languages).

@section Making Your Program Do Things: Procedures

The PROCEDURE DIVISION is where the action happens - this is your
program's recipe steps. Here you write the instructions that tell
the computer what to do.

@subsection Basic Statements

EIGHTBOL statements read like English sentences. Here are the most common:

@table @code
@item MOVE source TO destination
Copy data from one place to another
@item ADD amount TO variable
Add numbers together
@item SUBTRACT amount FROM variable
Subtract numbers
@item COMPUTE result = expression
Perform calculations
@item STRING source DELIMITED BY SIZE INTO dest
Block transfer (BLT): copy bytes from source to dest. Supports reference
modification: @code{name(start:length)} for partial buffer copy.
@end table

@example
    METHOD-ID. "Copy".
        PROCEDURE DIVISION.
        STRING SrcBuf(1:64) DELIMITED BY SIZE INTO DstBuf(1:64).
        GOBACK.
    END METHOD "Copy".
@end example

@strong{Note:} STRING with character delimiter is not supported; use
@code{DELIMITED BY SIZE} for block transfer only.

@subsection Unsupported Statements (compile-time error)

The following COBOL statements are not implemented and signal a compile-time
error: DIVIDE, MULTIPLY, UNSTRING, INSPECT (all forms), GOTO/GO TO,
EVALUATE, and SET forms other than @code{SET identifier TO expression}.

@example
    METHOD-ID. "Initialize".
        PROCEDURE DIVISION.
        MOVE 100 TO Player-Health.
        MOVE "Ready Player One" TO Game-Status.
        EXIT METHOD.
    END METHOD "Initialize".
@end example

@subsection Including Code: COPY Statements

Sometimes you want to reuse the same data definitions across multiple
programs. COBOL's COPY statement lets you include copybook files:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
PROGRAM-ID. Game-Logic.

DATA DIVISION.
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
COPY Game-Constants.     @c Include constants
COPY Player-Data.        @c Include player definitions

PROCEDURE DIVISION.
    MOVE Max-Health TO Player-Health
    GOBACK.
@end example

Copybooks use the WORKING-STORAGE SECTION with EXTERNAL data items
and USAGE BINARY for proper byte alignment:

@example
WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.
01  WS-SHARED-DATA EXTERNAL.
    05  Decal-XH USAGE BINARY 1.
    05  Player-Score USAGE BINARY 2.
@end example

Copybooks are searched for in the directories specified by the
@code{:include} parameter when compiling:

@example
(eightbol:compile-file "game-logic.cob"
                       :include '("Source/Generated" "Source/Classes"))
@end example

@subsection Organizing Code: Procedures

Procedures are like sub-recipes. Break complex tasks into smaller,
manageable pieces.

@example
PROCEDURE DIVISION.

Main-Game-Loop.
    PERFORM Handle-Input
    PERFORM Update-Game-State
    PERFORM Render-Screen
    PERFORM Check-Game-Over
    GOBACK.

Handle-Input.
    IF Button-A-Pressed THEN
        PERFORM Player-Jump
    END-IF
    GOBACK.

Player-Jump.
    ADD Jump-Power TO Player-Velocity-Y
    GOBACK.
@end example

Each procedure ends with GOBACK, which returns to the caller.

@subsection Making Decisions: IF Statements

Programs need to make choices based on conditions.

@example
IF Health-Points < 20 THEN
    MOVE 1 TO Low-Health-Flag
END-IF.
@end example

EIGHTBOL's IF statements read like English. You can include ELSE for alternatives:

@example
IF Enemy-Strength > Player-Level THEN
    PERFORM Run-Away
ELSE
    PERFORM Attack-Enemy
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Repeating Actions: Loops

Games often repeat actions, like updating all enemies.

@table @code
@item PERFORM procedure
Call a procedure once
@item PERFORM procedure UNTIL condition
Repeat until condition is true
@item PERFORM procedure VARYING var FROM start BY step UNTIL end
Count through a range
@end table

@example
PERFORM Update-All-Enemies.

PERFORM Process-Game-Turn UNTIL Game-Over = 1.

PERFORM Check-Enemy VARYING I FROM 1 BY 1 UNTIL I > Enemy-Count.
@end example

@subsection Multiple Choices: EVALUATE

When you have many options, EVALUATE is cleaner than nested IFs:

@example
EVALUATE Player-Choice
    WHEN 1
        PERFORM Start-New-Game
    WHEN 2
        PERFORM Load-Saved-Game
    WHEN 3
        PERFORM Show-Options
    WHEN OTHER
        MOVE 1 TO Invalid-Choice-Flag
END-EVALUATE.
@end example

@subsection Game Programming Extensions

EIGHTBOL includes special features for game development:

@table @code
@item property OF object
Access object properties (like Player.Health)
@item INVOKE object "method"
Call object methods
@item CALL subroutine IN BANK bank
Banked memory calls
@item LOG FAULT "code"
Log fault condition (uses LogFault)
@item BREAK FOR FAULT "code"
Break execution on fault (uses DebugBreak)
@end table

@example
INVOKE Player "TakeDamage" USING 25.

IF Health OF Player < 10 THEN
    LOG FAULT "LOWH"
END-IF.

BREAK FOR FAULT "CRIT" WHEN Health OF Player <= 0.
@end example

@section Expressions and Conditions

@cindex expressions
@cindex conditions
@cindex operators

EIGHTBOL expressions compare values and combine conditions.

@subsection Comparison Operators

EIGHTBOL uses words for comparisons, making them readable:

@table @code
@item A = B
A equals B
@item A <> B
A is not equal to B
@item A < B
A is less than B
@item A > B
A is greater than B
@item A <= B
A is less than or equal to B
@item A >= B
A is greater than or equal to B
@end table

@example
IF Player-Score >= High-Score THEN
    MOVE Player-Name TO Champion-Name
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Logical Operators

Combine conditions with AND, OR, and NOT:

@table @code
@item AND
Both conditions must be true
@item OR
At least one condition must be true
@item NOT
Reverse the condition
@end table

@example
IF Health > 0 AND Mana > 10 THEN
    MOVE 1 TO Spell-Ready-Flag
END-IF.

IF NOT Game-Over THEN
    PERFORM Continue-Game
END-IF.
@end example

@subsection Complex Conditions

You can combine multiple conditions:

@example
IF Player-Level >= 5 AND Has-Magic-Sword = 'Y' OR Is-Cheat-Mode = 1 THEN
    PERFORM Unlock-Secret-Level
END-IF.
@end example

@strong{Remember:} AND is evaluated before OR. Use parentheses if needed.

@section Doing Math: Arithmetic

EIGHTBOL provides several ways to calculate:

@example
ADD 100 TO Player-Score.

SUBTRACT Damage FROM Health-Points.

MULTIPLY Attack-Power BY 2 GIVING Total-Damage.

COMPUTE Final-Score = Base-Score + (Bonus * Multiplier).
@end example

@subsection Arithmetic Operations

@table @asis
@item ADD source TO destination
Add to existing value
@item ADD source TO destination GIVING result
Add and store in new variable
@item SUBTRACT source FROM destination
Subtract from existing value
@item MULTIPLY source BY destination
Multiply values
@item DIVIDE source INTO destination
Divide values
@item COMPUTE result = expression
Complex calculations
@end table

@subsection Try This: Score Calculation

@example
COMPUTE Final-Score = Base-Score + (Time-Bonus * 10) - Penalties.

COMPUTE Average-Damage = Total-Damage / Hit-Count.
@end example

@section Built-in Functions

@cindex functions
@cindex RANDOM
@cindex WHEN-COMPILED

EIGHTBOL provides special functions for game programming:

@table @code
@item RANDOM
Generate a random number (0-255)
@item RANDOM(seed)
Generate seeded random number
@item WHEN-COMPILED
Get compilation timestamp
@end table

@example
COMPUTE Random-Direction = RANDOM.

IF RANDOM > 128 THEN
    PERFORM Move-Right
ELSE
    PERFORM Move-Left
END-IF.
@end example

@section Common Programming Patterns

Here are patterns you'll use frequently:

@subsection Game Loop Pattern

@example
PROCEDURE DIVISION.
Main-Loop.
    PERFORM Read-Input
    PERFORM Update-Objects
    PERFORM Draw-Screen
    IF NOT Game-Over THEN
        GO TO Main-Loop
    END-IF
    PERFORM Show-Game-Over
    GOBACK.
@end example

@subsection State Machine Pattern

@example
EVALUATE Game-State
    WHEN 1  @c Title Screen
        PERFORM Show-Title
    WHEN 2  @c Playing
        PERFORM Run-Game
    WHEN 3  @c Game Over
        PERFORM Show-Results
END-EVALUATE.
@end example

@subsection Input Handling Pattern

@example
Check-Input.
    IF Left-Pressed THEN
        SUBTRACT 1 FROM Player-X
    END-IF
    IF Right-Pressed THEN
        ADD 1 TO Player-X
    END-IF
    IF Jump-Pressed AND On-Ground THEN
        MOVE 'Y' TO Is-Jumping
    END-IF
    GOBACK.
@end example

@section Best Practices

As you write more EIGHTBOL, follow these guidelines:

@enumerate
@item Use descriptive variable names (Player-Health, not PH)
@item Add comments explaining complex logic
@item Break large procedures into smaller ones
@item Initialize variables with VALUE clauses
@item Test procedures individually before combining
@item Use PERFORM instead of GO TO when possible
@item Keep procedures under 50 lines when practical
@end enumerate

@node CPU Backends
@chapter CPU Backends

@cindex CPU backends
@cindex target processors
@cindex assembly generation
@cindex ABI
@cindex calling convention

EIGHTBOL generates optimized assembly code for multiple CPU architectures.
Each backend documents its ABI (Application Binary Interface): register usage,
calling conventions, and procedure entry/exit. Hand-written assembly that
calls or is called by EIGHTBOL-generated code must follow these conventions.

@section 6502 Backend

@cindex 6502
@cindex MOS 6502

The 6502 backend generates code for the MOS 6502 processor family (6502, 65c02,
65c816, HuC6280, RP2A03). Output uses 64tass assembler syntax.

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item A
Accumulator; holds byte results and operands
@item X
X index register; used for indexing
@item Y
Y index register; used for slot offsets (ldy #Slot, lda (Self),y)
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call (PERFORM / CALL)
@code{jsr} to procedure label. Caller and callee share same bank.
Near @code{CALL} to a local label uses @code{jsr}; a tail @code{CALL} immediately before
@code{GOBACK}/@code{EXIT@dots{}} may use @code{jmp}.  Service, library, and bank-switched
forms use @code{.FarCall}, @code{.FarJSR}, or @code{jsr Lib.@dots{}} as appropriate.
@item Return
@code{rts}. No return value in registers.
@item INVOKE Self @code{"Method"}
@code{.CallMethod Call@var{Class}@var{Method}, @var{Class}Class} --- same Phantasia
@code{CallMethod} macro as @code{INVOKE} on a typed object (dispatches via @code{DoCallMethod}).
@item INVOKE variable @code{"Method"}
@code{.CallMethod Call@var{Type}@var{Method}, @var{Type}Class, @var{Var}}
@item Slot access
@code{ldy #@var{OriginClass}@var{Slot}; lda (Self),y} for slot OF Self
@item Caller-saved
A, X, Y may be clobbered by any call
@end table

@subsection Memory Access
6502 uses zero-page and absolute addressing. Variables map to direct addresses.

@section Z80 Backend

@cindex Z80
@cindex Zilog Z80

Z80 code generation. Output: lowercase Z80 assembly (ld a,(hl), etc.)

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item A
Accumulator (8-bit); byte results
@item HL
16-bit accumulator; word results, pointer for slot/array access
@item BC
Count register; loop counters, array indexing
@item DE
Destination pointer; block copy dest, temp for slot math
@item B
Temp for comparisons and bit ops
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call
@code{call @var{label}}. Return with @code{ret}.
@item Return value
Byte: in A. Word: in HL.
@item INVOKE Self
@code{call Invoke@var{Class}@var{Method}}
@item INVOKE variable
@code{call Call@var{Type}@var{Method}}
@item Caller-saved
A, HL, BC, DE, B may be clobbered. IX, IY not used by backend.
@end table

@section SM83 Backend (Game Boy)

@cindex SM83
@cindex Game Boy

SM83 (Sharp) is the Game Boy CPU, Z80/8080-like. Output: RGBDS syntax.

@subsection Registers
Same allocation as Z80: A=accumulator, HL=ptr, BC=count, DE=dest-ptr.

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@code{call} / @code{ret}. Byte return in A, word in HL. Same INVOKE
conventions as Z80.

@section CP1610 Backend (Intellivision)

@cindex CP1610
@cindex Intellivision

General Instrument CP1610, 16-bit RISC. Output: as1600 assembler syntax.

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item R0
Accumulator; 8-bit values use low byte
@item R1-R4
General purpose
@item R5
Return address for @code{JSR R5,addr}; @code{JR R5} returns
@item R6
Stack pointer
@item R7
Program counter
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call
@code{JSR R5, @var{label}}. Return address in R5; callee returns with @code{JR R5}.
@item Return value
In R0 (byte or word)
@item Caller-saved
R0-R4 may be clobbered. R5, R6 must be preserved.
@end table

@section M68K Backend (68000)

@cindex M68K
@cindex Motorola 68000

Motorola 68000. Output: GAS/AT&T syntax (move.b, move.w).

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item D0
Accumulator; byte/word results
@item D1
Temp for expressions
@item A0
Address temp, slot/array base
@item A7
Stack pointer
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call
@code{jsr @var{label}}. Return with @code{rts}.
@item Return value
Byte/word in D0
@item Caller-saved
D0, D1, A0 may be clobbered. A1-A6, D2-D7 callee-saved if used.
@end table

@section i286 Backend (Intel 80286)

@cindex i286
@cindex 80286
@cindex Intel

Intel 80286, 16-bit. Output: Intel syntax (.286, .model small).

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item AL/AX
Accumulator; AL for byte, AX for word
@item BL/BX
Temp; byte or word
@item CX
Temp for bit ops, loop count (STRING)
@item SI
Index for array/subscript access
@item DI
Destination pointer for block copy
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call
@code{call @var{label}}. Return with @code{ret}.
@item Return value
Byte in AL, word in AX
@item INVOKE
@code{call Invoke@var{Class}@var{Method}} or @code{call Call@var{Type}@var{Method}}
@item Caller-saved
AX, BX, CX, SI, DI may be clobbered. BP, SP preserved.
@end table

@section ARM7 Backend (ARM7TDMI)

@cindex ARM7
@cindex ARM7TDMI

ARM7TDMI. Output: Thumb-mode GAS assembly.

@subsection Registers
@table @code
@item R0
Accumulator; byte/word results
@item R1
Temp, dest pointer
@item R2
Source pointer, temp
@item R13 (SP)
Stack pointer
@item R14 (LR)
Link register; @code{bx lr} returns
@end table

@subsection ABI and Calling Conventions
@table @asis
@item Procedure call
@code{bl @var{label}}. Return with @code{bx lr}.
@item Return value
In R0
@item Caller-saved
R0, R1, R2 may be clobbered. R4-R11 callee-saved.
@end table

@node Examples
@chapter Examples

@cindex examples
@cindex sample programs

Let's learn by doing! This chapter provides complete, working examples
you can compile and run. Start with simple programs and build up to
more complex ones.

@section Your First Object: Game Manager

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. GameManager.

OBJECT.
    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "ShowWelcome".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            MOVE "Welcome to EIGHTBOL Gaming!" TO Message.
            MOVE "Ready Player One..." TO Subtitle.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "ShowWelcome".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS GameManager.
@end example

@strong{Try This:} Create a GameManager object and call its ShowWelcome method.

@section Simple Calculator Object

Let's create a calculator object that performs basic math:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Calculator.

OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.
        COPY CalculatorData.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "Add".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            ADD Number-A TO Number-B GIVING Result.
            GOBACK GIVING Result.
        END METHOD "Add".

        METHOD-ID. "Subtract".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            SUBTRACT Number-B FROM Number-A GIVING Result.
            GOBACK GIVING Result.
        END METHOD "Subtract".

        METHOD-ID. "Multiply".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            MULTIPLY Number-A BY Number-B GIVING Result.
            GOBACK GIVING Result.
        END METHOD "Multiply".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS Calculator.
@end example

@strong{Modify It:} Add a division method and change the numbers.

@section Simple Game Character

Let's create a character that can take damage:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Game-Character INHERITS Basic-Object.

OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.
    COPY CharacterInstanceData.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "Take-Damage".
        DATA DIVISION.
        LINKAGE SECTION.
        01 Damage-Amount PIC 9(3).
        PROCEDURE DIVISION USING BY VALUE Damage-Amount.
            SUBTRACT Damage-Amount FROM Health-Points
            IF Health-Points < 1 THEN
                INVOKE SELF "Die"
            ELSE
                MOVE 1 TO Damage-Taken-Flag
            END-IF
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Take-Damage".

        METHOD-ID. "Heal".
        DATA DIVISION.
        LINKAGE SECTION.
        01 Heal-Amount PIC 9(3).
        PROCEDURE DIVISION USING BY VALUE Heal-Amount.
            ADD Heal-Amount TO Health-Points
            IF Health-Points > Max-Health THEN
                MOVE Max-Health TO Health-Points
            END-IF
            MOVE 1 TO Healed-Flag
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Heal".

        METHOD-ID. "Die".
        PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            MOVE 1 TO Dead-Flag
            LOG FAULT "DEAD"
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Die".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS Game-Character.
@end example

@section Complete Game: Number Guessing

Here's a complete, playable game:

@example
IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
CLASS-ID. Number-Guessing-Game.

OBJECT.
    DATA DIVISION.
        COPY GuessingGameData.

    PROCEDURE DIVISION.

        METHOD-ID. "Initialize".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            COMPUTE Secret-Number = RANDOM.
            MOVE 0 TO Guess-Count.
            MOVE 'N' TO Game-Over.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "Initialize".

        METHOD-ID. "MakeGuess".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION USING Guess-Value.
            MOVE Guess-Value TO Player-Guess.
            ADD 1 TO Guess-Count.

            IF Player-Guess = Secret-Number THEN
                MOVE 3 TO Guess-Result  @c Correct!
                MOVE 'Y' TO Game-Over
            ELSE
                IF Player-Guess < Secret-Number THEN
                    MOVE 1 TO Guess-Result  @c Too low
                ELSE
                    MOVE 2 TO Guess-Result  @c Too high
                END-IF
            END-IF.
            EXIT METHOD.
        END METHOD "MakeGuess".

        METHOD-ID. "GetResult".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            GOBACK GIVING Guess-Result.
        END METHOD "GetResult".

        METHOD-ID. "IsGameOver".
            PROCEDURE DIVISION.
            IF Game-Over = 'Y' THEN
                GOBACK GIVING 1
            ELSE
                GOBACK GIVING 0
            END-IF.
        END METHOD "IsGameOver".
END OBJECT.

END CLASS Number-Guessing-Game.
@end example

@section Tips for Writing Your Own Objects

As you write more EIGHTBOL programs, here are some helpful tips:

@enumerate
@item Start simple - get one feature working at a time
@item Test methods individually before combining them
@item Keep methods short and focused on one task
@item Use meaningful variable and method names
@item Use COPY statements for data definitions
@item Comment complex logic
@item Use return values to communicate results
@item Experiment with different approaches
@end enumerate

@strong{Remember:} Every expert programmer started as a beginner. The key
is to practice regularly and learn from each program you write!

@node Troubleshooting
@chapter Troubleshooting

@cindex troubleshooting
@cindex errors
@cindex debugging

Common issues and their solutions.

@section Compilation Errors

@subsection Undefined Variable
@code{MOVE 1 TO UndefinedVar} generates an error because the variable
isn't declared in DATA DIVISION.

@strong{Solution:} Declare all variables in WORKING-STORAGE SECTION.

@subsection Invalid PIC Clause
String variables (PIC X) are not supported.

@strong{Solution:} Use byte arrays or numeric variables instead.

@section Runtime Issues

@subsection Stack Overflow
Deep recursion can cause stack overflow on 8-bit systems.

@strong{Solution:} Use iteration instead of recursion where possible.

@subsection Memory Limits
8-bit systems have limited RAM.

@strong{Solution:} Minimize variable usage and optimize data structures.

@section Platform-Specific Issues

@subsection 6502 Zero Page
6502 code uses zero-page addressing for efficiency.

@subsection Z80 Memory Banking
Z80 systems may require bank switching for large programs.

